Changes in CO2 Emissions Over Time Members: Katherine Amundson, Kendra Scace, Gautham Suresh, Kelly Ryan

Introduction

Understanding the historical trends of CO2 emissions is essential for crafting policies and strategies to mitigate their impact. In this project, we explore the changes in CO2 emissions overtime, focusing on different aspects such as the comparison of emission patterns between certain countries, impact of international agreements, and specific countries with the highest emissions. Along with that, we showed comparisons of CO2 emissions over time and the difference in emissions between developed and developing countries.

Data

We utilized a comprehensive dataset on CO2 emissions by country from 1750 to 2022. The dataset includes information on each countrys emissions, population, area, and relevant codes. After loading the data, we conducted data cleaning to handle missing values and ensure the datasets integrity.

The dataset contains information about CO2 emissions from different countries over a significant period, from 1750 to 2020. The dataset comprises 9 columns:

  1. Country: Represents the name of the country.

  2. Code: Corresponds to the countrys abbreviation or code.

  3. Calling Code: Refers to the area code in a phone number associated with the country.

  4. Year: Denotes the year when the data was observed.

  5. CO2 Emission (Tons): Represents the recorded amount of CO2 emissions by the country for a specific year.

  6. Population as of 2022: Indicates the number of people living in the country as of the year 2022.

  7. Area: Represents the size of the country in square kilometers.

  8. Percent of World: Indicates the proportion of the Earths surface area occupied by the country.

  9. Density in km2: Represents the population density of the country calculated as the number of people per square kilometer.

Dataset Overview:

  • The dataset contains 59,620 rows, each representing a unique combination of country, year, and associated data.

  • The years covered in the dataset range from 1750 to 2020.

  • The CO2 emissions column reveals a wide range of values, from 0 to 4.17e+11 (4.17e11 represents 4.17 multiplied by 10 to the power of 11).

  • The population column shows variations in population size, with a minimum of 11,310 and a maximum of 1.426e+09 (1.426e09 represents 1.426 multiplied by 10 to the power of 9).

  • The dataset also includes information about the size of each country, its share of the world, and population density.

Filter Non-Zero CO2 Emissions:

This step involves excluding entries with zero CO2 emissions, focusing on non-zero emission instances. This filtered dataset has 21,707 rows and 9 columns.

df <- df %>%
  filter(CO2.emission..Tons. != 0)

Determining Minimum CO2 Emission Years:

For each country, the year with the minimum CO2 emissions is determined, and the corresponding data is summarized. This results in a dataset that provides insights into the earliest year with non-zero CO2 emissions for each country, for which we printed the head.

min_year_data <- df %>%
  group_by(Country) %>%
  filter(CO2.emission..Tons. != 0) %>%
  summarise(Min_Year = min(Year),
            CO2_Emission = CO2.emission..Tons.[which.min(Year)])

head(min_year_data)

Methods

Our analysis involved various methods, including data cleaning, exploratory data analysis, and visualizations. The methods can be categorized into data handling, exploratory data analysis (EDA), and visualization techniques. The primary tools utilized for these tasks were the dplyr and ggplot2 packages in R.

Our methodology encompassed thorough data cleaning, exploratory data analysis, and diverse visualizations to uncover patterns and trends in CO2 emissions across countries, with a specific focus on the impact of international agreements, top emitters, and the comparison between countries like China and the United States. The use of R packages, particularly dplyr and ggplot2, facilitated efficient data manipulation and visualization

Results

Changes Over Time

We started by examining how emissions have evolved over time for different countries. For countries with data available before 1900, we visualized their emission trends. This helped us identify early industrializers and compare their patterns with currently developing countries.

# Filter countries with Min_Year < 1900
selected_countries <- min_year_data %>%
  filter(Min_Year < 1900)

# Filter data for selected countries
selected_df <- df %>%
  filter(Country %in% selected_countries$Country)

# Get the top 10 countries based on some criterion (e.g., average CO2 emissions)
top_10_countries <- selected_df %>%
  group_by(Country) %>%
  summarize(avg_emission = mean(CO2.emission..Tons.)) %>%
  top_n(10, wt = avg_emission) %>%
  pull(Country)

# Filter the data for the top 10 countries
selected_df_top10 <- selected_df %>%
  filter(Country %in% top_10_countries)

# Plotting
ggplot(selected_df_top10, aes(x = Year, y = CO2.emission..Tons., color = Country)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Top 10 CO2 Emissions of Countries with Min Year < 1900",
       x = "Year",
       y = "CO2 Emission (Tons)") +
  theme_minimal() + scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma)

population_threshold <- 75000000  # 75 million

large_countries <- df %>%
  filter(Population.2022. > population_threshold)

Impact of International Agreements

We investigated whether international agreements have influenced CO2 emissions by examining emission trends for countries with populations exceeding 75 million. The visualizations included vertical lines representing the years of key international agreements. The Kyoto Protocol, created in 1997, and the Paris Agreement, enacted in 2015, are two of the most influential climate agreements to date, so we chose to use those as our markers.

Global Distribution

To understand the geographical distribution of emissions in 2020, we created a world map highlighting each countrys contribution.

# Load world map data
world_map <- map_data("world")
# Rename regions for consistency
world_map <- world_map %>%
  mutate(region = case_when(
    region == "UK"  ~ "United Kingdom",
    region == "USA" ~ "United States",
    TRUE ~ region
  ))
# Filter the data for the year 2020
df_2020 <- df %>% filter(Year == 2020)
# Perform inner join with the world map data
merged_data <- inner_join(world_map, df_2020, by = c("region" = "Country"))
# Plot the global distribution of CO2 emissions for the year 2020
ggplot(merged_data, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = CO2.emission..Tons.)) +
  geom_polygon(color = "white") +
  labs(title = "Global Distribution of CO2 Emissions (Year 2020)",
       fill = "CO2 Emissions (Tons)") +
  theme_map()

The map provides a visual representation of the global distribution of CO2 emissions, allowing for the identification of regions or countries with notable emission levels. Patterns and concentrations of high or low emissions can be observed, providing insights into the geographical variations of carbon dioxide output

Comparing CO2 US and China for the past 60 years shows a general trend where the emissions rate for China is climbing faster than the US. This lines up with historical context as companies tend to move manufacturing plants to countries with looser labor laws and restrictions.

CO2 Emissions Comparison

In this section, we delve into a detailed analysis of CO2 emissions data, focusing on the year 2020. The dataset under consideration includes information on CO2 emissions, population figures, and additional pertinent variables across various countries.

  1. Data Preprocessing:

Column Renaming: For enhanced readability and ease of use, columns were renamed. The column CO2.emission..Tons. was abbreviated to coTons, while Population.2022. became population.

Data Sorting: To facilitate subsequent analyses, the dataset was sorted in descending order based on population.

  1. Analysis for the Year 2020:

Filtering Data: The dataset was filtered to exclusively include entries where the Year column corresponds to 2020.

Handling NaN Values: A subset of data was extracted where at least one value had NaN on all columns.

Top 10 Countries in 2020

Focusing on the top 10 countries with the highest CO2 emissions in the year 2020. A subset of the dataset was created by selecting the top 10 countries with the highest CO2 emissions. It was visualized over the course of the year using a line plot with various colors. United States shows to be leading, while China is second and just over half of the USs emissions.

# Select the top 10 countries with the highest CO2 emissions in 2020
top10_2020 <- df2020 %>% arrange(desc(coTons)) %>% head(10)

# Filter the original dataset for the selected countries

Now we reach the 1900s, at first glance the graph seems like the other countries didnt add much to the CO2 emissions and the US just skyrocketed. If you look at the numbers on the y-axis, you will see that the US is just an outlier, and the other countries have actually doubled their CO2. Many factors could lead to this jump. One of them could be the post World-War II baby boom, an increase in population equals an increase in CO2 emissions.

Developing vs Developed Countries

gdp_threshold <- 25000

df_categorized <- wdi_data %>%
  mutate(GDP_per_capita = NY.GDP.MKTP.KD / SP.POP.TOTL)


df_categorized <- df_categorized %>%
  mutate(development_status = ifelse(GDP_per_capita >= gdp_threshold, "Developed", "Developing"))

df_categorized <- na.omit(df_categorized)

developed_countries <- df_categorized %>%
  filter(development_status == "Developed")

developing_countries <- df_categorized %>%
  filter(development_status == "Developing")
emissions_2020 <- df_categorized %>%
  filter(Year == 2020)

top_developed <- emissions_2020 %>%
  filter(development_status == "Developed") %>%
  top_n(10, wt = CO2.emission..Tons.)

top_developing <- emissions_2020 %>%
  filter(development_status == "Developing") %>%
  top_n(10, wt = CO2.emission..Tons.)

# Plot emissions for the top 10 developed countries in 2020
developed_plot <- ggplot(top_developed, aes(x = reorder(Country, -CO2.emission..Tons.), y = CO2.emission..Tons., fill = development_status)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Top 10 CO2 Emissions in 2020: Developed Countries",
       x = "Country",
       y = "CO2 Emissions (Tons)",
       fill = "Development Status") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  coord_flip()

# Plot emissions for the top 10 developing countries in 2020
developing_plot <- ggplot(top_developing, aes(x = reorder(Country, -CO2.emission..Tons.), y = CO2.emission..Tons., fill = development_status)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Top 10 CO2 Emissions in 2020: Developing Countries",
       x = "Country",
       y = "CO2 Emissions (Tons)",
       fill = "Development Status") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  coord_flip()

print(developed_plot)

print(developing_plot)

India is 2nd to China in terms of CO2 emissions. As more companies attempt to gain a foothold in India for setting up manufacturing plants, it would be interesting to see in the future whether Indias CO2 emissions rise as Chinas falls

Conclusion

Our analysis provides valuable insights into the changing landscape of CO2 emissions. We observed historical emission patterns, the impact of international agreements, and the contributions of specific countries. Understanding these trends is crucial for policymakers and stakeholders working towards sustainable environmental practices.

Historical Emission Patterns

Our exploration of historical emission patterns provided a comprehensive view of how different countries have contributed to the cumulative CO2 emissions since 1750. By identifying the starting points of recorded emissions for each country, we gained insights into the trajectories of their carbon footprints over time. This historical context aids in understanding the varying roles nations have played in the global emissions landscape.

Impact of International Agreements

Our analysis delved into the impact of international agreements on CO2 emissions, specifically focusing on countries with populations exceeding 75 million. Visualizing emissions trends alongside the dates of major agreements revealed nuanced shifts in emission patterns following international efforts. This aspect of our study sheds light on the effectiveness of collaborative initiatives in curbing and fostering a more sustainable future.

Significance for Policymakers and Stakeholders

The insights derived from our analysis carry significant implications for policymakers and stakeholders dedicated to environmental sustainability. Policymakers can leverage this information to design tailored strategies for emission reduction, accounting for historical contributions and the impact of international collaborations. Stakeholders, including environmental organizations and businesses, can use these findings to align their efforts with global objectives and contribute to a more sustainable and resilient future.

Future Considerations

As we progress towards a more environmentally conscious future, continued monitoring and analysis of CO2 emissions remain imperative. Ongoing assessments will enable us to evaluate the effectiveness of current policies, identify emerging trends, and adapt strategies to address evolving challenges. Additionally, exploring the intersection of CO2 emissions with socioeconomic factors, technological advancements, and policy implementations can provide a holistic understanding of the forces shaping our environmental trajectory.

In conclusion, our analysis not only illuminates the historical context of CO2 emissions but also offers a roadmap for informed decision-making in the pursuit of a sustainable and resilient global ecosystem. As we collectively strive for a greener future, the lessons drawn from this study can serve as valuable guides for shaping impactful policies and fostering a shared commitment to environmental stewardship.
